	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Sustainable  fishery agreements: strategies for enforcement and compliance</h1>

			
			<h4>
												29 April 2013
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>A conference organised by the International Seafood Sustainability Foundation (ISSF) entitled ‘Sustainable fishery agreements: Strategies for enforcement and compliance’ brought together tuna fisheries stakeholders who promote rights-based management (industry, negotiators, regional fisheries management organisations/RFMO representatives, NGOs). The conference identified a number of actions that should be considered to improve compliance through rights-based (and other) management arrangements, supported by effective enforcement.</p><p>‘Compliance’ is understood as the application of and adherence to agreed measures by RFMO members, cooperating non-members, individuals and vessels under the jurisdiction of those members; while ‘enforcement’ is a set of tools for monitoring the implementation of these agreed measures, promoting compliance, applying penalties for non-compliance and deterring third parties from undermining the conservation measures adopted by RFMOs.</p><p>Key points were highlighted by the participants, including:</p>
<ul>

<li>Adopting a rights-based management system is more difficult in a multinational context. Based on case studies of rights-based management systems, it would be useful to assess their possible application in the RFMO/multinational context.</li>

<li>Enforcement increasingly covers the whole value chain, and tools are diversifying beyond flag state control over vessels (catch documentation schemes, etc.). Multilateral compliance measures, including illegal, unregulated or unreported (IUU) lists, trade measures, port state controls and observer programmes are increasingly developed.</li>

<li>A link can be made between compliance and allocation of fishing opportunities – the legitimacy of measures, which influences the level of compliance, is strongly related to transparency and perceived fairness of allocation of fishing opportunities and rules about their use.</li>

</ul>
<p>One of the main issues raised by participants is the cost associated with enforcement: ‘compliance and enforcement for fishery management systems are believed to be less costly when there are fewer, large vessels, and more difficult when there are many small vessels.’ They argued that rights-based management has clear advantages, as they promote aggregate profitability of fishing, which in turn facilitates monitoring and verification.</p><p>However, important investments are needed for improving institutional capacity: ‘this will involve providing assistance to some members and strengthening RFMO secretariats.’</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>ISSF, ‘Sustainable fisheries agreements: Strategies for enforcement and compliance’, 3&nbsp;March 2013</p><p>
<a href="http://iss-foundation.org/wp-content/uploads/downloads/2013/03/maui_conference_report_030313.pdf" target="_self">http://iss-foundation.org/wp-content/uploads/downloads/2013/03/maui_conf...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Currently, ‘rights-based management systems’ – in this case, systems where there is a market for fishing rights that can be transferred between users – are not implemented in any tuna RFMOs. If such management systems were proposed, it would be important for ACP countries participating in tuna RFMOs to carefully assess the economic, social and environmental costs and benefits of such systems, and whether they will deliver results in line with ACP tuna fisheries development plans. The view that ‘a small number of large vessels are easier to manage than many small ones’ is a bit simplistic in the case of tuna fisheries. Other elements also come into the equation, including local landings: most large tuna vessels are foreign, and often tranship their catches at sea rather than landing them in ACP ports, which is an element making the enforcement of management measures more difficult.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
